  "body": "`React.renderComponentToString` does not appear to render selection state for `select` elements.\n\nGiven [this example](http://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/1408993/react-html-render-issue.html):\n\n``` html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html>\n  <head>\n    <meta charset=\"utf-8\">\n    <script src=\"//fb.me/react-0.10.0.js\"></script>\n    <script>window.onload = function() {\n      function select() {\n        return React.DOM.select(\n          {value: \"c\", defaultValue: \"c\"},\n          React.DOM.option({value: \"a\"}, \"a\"),\n          React.DOM.option({value: \"b\"}, \"b\"),\n          React.DOM.option({value: \"c\"}, \"c\")\n        )\n      }\n\n      var divs = document.querySelectorAll(\"div\")\n\n      divs[0].innerHTML = React.renderComponentToString(select())\n      React.renderComponent(select(), divs[1])\n    }</script>\n  </head>\n  <body>\n    <div></div>\n    <div></div>\n  </body>\n</html>\n```\n\nThe HTML is rendered like this:\n\n![screen shot 2014-06-11 at 7 58 55 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4433/3252601/5f07db2c-f1c4-11e3-8a34-9af2ae003d0b.png)\n\nWhich means that selection state is only applied once the markup hits the client. The only way to preserve selection state through `React.renderComponentToString` is to set the `selected` property on each `option`, which results in these warnings on both the client and server:\n\n![screen shot 2014-06-11 at 8 01 38 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/4433/3252621/c33d1936-f1c4-11e3-925a-8ee3cc7edaa9.png)\n\nIn my opinion, the server and client experience should be identical, and selection state should not depend on whether the client JavaScript has loaded.\n",
